  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1540677101" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1540677101" />
    <a title="Jim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7627123-jim"><img alt="Jim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1328453125p2/7627123.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1540677101?book_show_action=true">Feb 07, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jim" href="/user/show/7627123-jim">Jim</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7627123-jim?shelf=2016">2016</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1540677101" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15349386908095557731">After really enjoying author Scott Pratt&apos;s open book in his Joe Dillard series, I had high hopes for the second book, &quot;In Good Faith&quot;. However, I&apos;d have to say for me it was an incredible let down. The plot was constructed with so many branches it was tough weeding through the weak ones to finding the stronger ones. Sometimes less is more. The story in this outing was all over the place. Some of the twists and gyrations were just ridiculous. This time out, It&apos;s been a year since Joe completed th</span>
  <span id="freeText15349386908095557731" style="display:none">After really enjoying author Scott Pratt's open book in his Joe Dillard series, I had high hopes for the second book, "In Good Faith". However, I'd have to say for me it was an incredible let down. The plot was constructed with so many branches it was tough weeding through the weak ones to finding the stronger ones. Sometimes less is more. The story in this outing was all over the place. Some of the twists and gyrations were just ridiculous. This time out, It's been a year since Joe completed the Angel Christian case, and he's bored silly. Joe's wife Caroline prods him to go see D.A. Lee Mooney to ask for a job. Time for a change and put the bad guys in jail instead of keeping them out. Of course right out of the chute Joe steps on toes as he's assigned a fresh case, where the brutal slaying of a family showed signs of Satanic rituals involved. Almost right away another double murder happens with the same signs of Satanic markings presented in the previous killings. The police are looking for two young men and one young female in connection with the killings. Joe has to worry about a colleague working behind his back leaking details to the press. Joe's boss seems detached from the case and seemingly from doing his own job. Things fall apart for Joe when Caroline is diagnosed with breast cancer. While dealing with Caroline and trying to track down two pretty odd twin girls the story keeps getting stuck. When the sheriff comes to Joe with massive corruption case leading to top of D.A.'s office he has to further divide his time. With all of the action sequences Joe gets involved with and the many offshoots of the plot it gets very slow to read. The pages at times painfully tick away, and by the end I really didn't care what happened to who. The ending itself was pure farce and just ridiculous. It's hard to say which way author Scott Pratt will take Joe Dillard in following five books. Either he'll have to go back to defending bad guys or find another career altogether. I was really bummed this book slid into mishmosh. Maybe (?), Joe working as ADA could make for some pretty good legal thrillers. I'm giving "In Good Faith" a real Christmas present with three stars out of a possible five stars. It really did not deserve more than two stars. However, I'm going to read the next couple Joe Dillard's and hope they make a huge comeback before I delete out of my Kindle. Hopefully readers will like this second outing far better than I did. My high hopes for the series are hanging precariously. See if you can help out author Scott Pratt with a higher rating for "In Good Faith". I'm not seeing it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15349386908095557731" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1540677101">
  <td colspan="2">
